**Abstract:**
Essay dated September 26, 1993, titled "Philosophy and Theology." The document reflects on a Georgetown University symposium where participants rejected the philosophy-theology distinction as obsolete. It analyzes Aquinas's distinction between philosophy (assent based on evidence) and theology (assent based on divine authority), arguing this distinction is only conceivable from the believer's standpoint. The essay explores whether abandoning this distinction implies abandoning the intellectualistic approach, and develops the view that faith is more akin to practical knowledge than to contemplative assent.

**AI Recommendation:** Important essay on philosophy-theology distinction; reflects author's engagement with contemporary debates while developing historical critique.

